 :itonami.blueprint/implemented-slice
 "`:fabricated-metal-repair-governor` is implemented end-to-end in
 `src/fabricated_metal_repair` as a REPAIR-SHOP OPERATIONS COORDINATION
 actor -- Repair Advisor (LLM proposal-only) ⊣ Repair Governor (closed-
 op-allowlist / equipment-verification / legal-basis / unresolved-concern
 hard-gates). ISIC 3311 covers repair of FABRICATED METAL PRODUCTS
 specifically -- structural steel members/frames, storage tanks,
 boilers/pressure vessels and metal furniture -- distinct from the more
 specific/other repair classes 3312 (machinery and equipment), 3313
 (electronic and optical equipment), 3314 (electrical equipment), 3315
 (transport equipment) and the residual class 3319 (other equipment).
 This actor deliberately holds NO repair-equipment/welding-tool control
 authority and NO return-to-service sign-off authority (both are HARD,
 permanent governor blocks, never overridable by human approval -- see
 `fabricated-metal-repair.governor` ns docstring), the SAME
 coordination-only, narrower-than-4211 shape `cloud-itonami-isic-3314`
 (Repair of Electrical Equipment) and `cloud-itonami-isic-3319` (Repair of
 Other Equipment) already established in this fleet. Every one of its
 four proposal ops (`:log-repair-record` / `:schedule-repair-operation` /
 `:flag-safety-concern` / `:order-supplies`) carries `:effect :propose`
 ONLY -- the governor HARD-holds any proposal that doesn't
 (`effect-not-propose-violations`), a structural invariant distinguishing
 this actor from siblings that DO commit real-world actuation effects.

 Like `cloud-itonami-isic-3314` and `cloud-itonami-isic-3319`, this
 actor's `:schedule-repair-operation` MAY auto-commit at phase 3 when the
 governor is completely clean -- equipment/work-order independently
 verified, a per-jurisdiction pre-return-to-service weld-repair-
 inspection legal basis on file, and no unresolved safety concern on
 record. The schedule op itself is still only ever a proposed
 diagnostic/repair/testing WINDOW, never a live-work authorization, a
 repair-equipment/welding-tool control command, or a return-to-service
 sign-off -- and this actor's own HARD checks (equipment-verification,
 legal-basis-on-file citing the jurisdiction's own post-repair
 inspection duty, no-unresolved-safety-concern) plus its forbidden-
 action-class block on any `:return-to-service-sign-off?` marker already
 gate the actual structural/pressure-integrity hazard surface
 independently of phase. `:flag-safety-concern` is the ONLY permanent,
 unconditional `high-stakes` member in `fabricated-metal-repair.governor`
 -- see that ns docstring 'Actuation' section for the full rationale.

 Per-jurisdiction (JPN/USA/DEU/SWE) post-repair (weld-repair on a
 pressure-bearing/structural part) inspection-before-return-to-service
 legal-basis catalog (`fabricated-metal-repair.facts`) with real official
 sources -- all FOUR seeded jurisdictions are honestly `:qualitative`
 here (a procedural change-notification-plus-inspection /
 pressure-test-or-NDE / qualified-inspector duty before a repaired
 pressure vessel, boiler or structural-load-bearing member returns to
 service, not a fixed numeric notice-lead-time count), the same
 honest-coverage convention `installation.facts`/`demolition.facts`/
 `construction.facts`/`electrical-equipment-repair.facts`/`other-
 equipment-repair.facts` establish. This actor does not invent a numeric
 lead-time count where none of its four researched jurisdictions'
 fabricated-metal-product repair law gives one for the repair itself.
 This build ships NO JVM-only interop anywhere in `src/` (no real
 Resend/Twilio transports -- `fabricated-metal-repair.notify` ships only
 the portable mock notifier + `Notifier` protocol seam) per this
 workspace's cljs-first `.cljc` runtime-priority rule. `:flag-safety-
 concern` ALWAYS escalates to a human, at every phase, unconditionally.
 See `docs/` -- README `Actuation` section -- for the full governor-check
 enumeration and the rationale for each hard/soft rule."}
